<section xml:id="Cross_Product">
  <title>Cross Product</title>
  <p>
    Maybe not include...only found in Sullivan and Stewart books and no other books.
  </p>
  <p>
    For vector spaces, and only for vector spaces,
    there is a second way to define a product of two vectors.
    In this section,
    we will discuss the cross-product of vectors which will allow us to find a vector that is perpendicular to the two given vectors.
  </p>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>\mathbf{u}=\langle a_1,a_2,a_3\rangle</m> and
        <m>\mathbf{v}=\langle b_1,b_2,b_3\rangle</m> are three-dimensional vectors,
        then the <term>cross product</term>
            <idx><h>cross product</h></idx>
        of <m>\mathbf{u}</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}</m> is defined to be the vector
        <me>
          \mathbf{u}\times\mathbf{v}=\langle a_2b_3-a_3b_2,a_3b_1-a_1b_3,a_1b_2-a_2b_1\rangle
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <p>
    Example: A boat is sailing on a bearing of
    <m>89^{\circ}</m> east of north at 564 feet per min.
    A tail wind is adding to the plane's velocity and blowing
    <m>78^{\circ}</m> west of north at 25 feet per min.
    Determine the actual speed of the plane in mph.
  </p>
  <p>
    Ans: The boat is moving at 540 feet per min = 6.14mph
  </p>
